				 Sen apology
																								New Delhi, Nov. 2: Indias ambassador to the US, Ronen Sen, today offered an unqualified apology to the Rajya Sabha privileges committee for his headless chicken remark reports our special correspondent..																								It was an act of indiscretion and it should not have been done, Sen reportedly told the committee headed by Rajya Sabha deputy chairman K. Rahman Khan.																								Committee sources said Sen was likely to be let off with a reprimand. A final decision will be taken on November 19.																								On Monday, Sen had similarly apologised before the Lok Sabha privileges committee.																								The Rajya Sabha panel apparently demanded to know how an experienced envoy like him could commit such an indiscretion and whether there was more to it.																								Sen denied such suggestions, the sources said. He clarified that headless chickens was a colloquial phrase that should not have been used.																								He said what he had told the journalist was a private conversation not meant even for a third person. However, if I have unwittingly hurt any sentiments, I offer my unqualified apologies.																								Asked why he had not filed a case against the journalist, he said it would not have been befitting his status, the sources said.																								A media interview had quoted Sen as saying: Why do you have all this running around like headless chicken, looking for a comment here or comment there, and these little storms in a tea cup?
